\begin_layout Subsection
Laboratory coordinates
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Laboratory-coordinates"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formed by the basis set:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}=\left\{ \boldsymbol{l}_{1},\boldsymbol{l}_{2},\boldsymbol{l}_{3}\mid\boldsymbol{l}_{i}\boldsymbol{l}_{j}=\delta_{ij}\right\} =\mathcal{L}_{xy}\bigcup\left\{ \boldsymbol{l}_{3}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{\mathcal{L}}=\mathscr{L}_{\mathbb{R}}(\mathcal{L})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{l}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is an unit vector pointing the direction of the incident beam.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{l}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is just a unit vector normal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{l}_{2}$
\end_inset

 and parallel to the surface plane.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{l}_{3}$
\end_inset

 is a unit vector perpendicular to both, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{l}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{l}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\mathcal{L}}$
\end_inset

 is the space spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 with real coefficients.
 The subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{xy}$
\end_inset

 was defined for future convenience.
 It spans the surface space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Representations of vector in this basis will be labeled as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{v}=\sum_{i=1}^{3}v_{i}\boldsymbol{l}_{i}\,\rightarrow\,\underline{v}_{\mathcal{L}}=\begin{pmatrix}v_{1}\\
v_{2}\\
v_{3}
\end{pmatrix}\in\mathbb{R}^{3}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{v}=\sum_{i=1}^{2}v_{i}\boldsymbol{l}_{i}\,\rightarrow\,\underline{v}_{\mathcal{L}_{xy}}=\begin{pmatrix}v_{1}\\
v_{2}
\end{pmatrix}\in\mathbb{R}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Auxiliary coordinates
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Auxiliary-coordinates"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formed by the basis set: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{A}=\left\{ \boldsymbol{a}_{1},\boldsymbol{a}_{2}\mid\boldsymbol{a}_{i}\boldsymbol{a}_{j}=\delta_{ij}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{\mathcal{A}}=\mathscr{L}_{\mathbb{R}}(\mathcal{A})=\mathscr{L}_{\mathbb{R}}(\mathcal{L}_{xy})\subset E_{\mathcal{L}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a unit vector pointing to one of the main directions of the surface.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a unit vector perpendicular to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The only difference between these coordinates and the ones defined before
 in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Laboratory-coordinates"

\end_inset

 is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

-coordinates are tilted respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 by an angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At this point we are able to define transformations from auxiliary coordinates
 to laboratory ones.
 In general our transformation matrices will operate on a desired representation
 to give the correct representation in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 but sometimes we will prefer to obtain the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

-representation.
 In the last case, matrices will have the sub-index 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

aux
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 As a first step, we will define 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{l}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{l}_{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

 coordinates:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{l_{1}}_{\mathcal{L}_{xy}}=\begin{pmatrix}\cos\beta\\
\sin\beta
\end{pmatrix}\,\,;\,\,\underline{l_{2}}_{\mathcal{L}_{xy}}=\begin{pmatrix}-\sin\beta\\
\cos\beta
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with this, we can define the transformation matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{\underline{A}}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{v}_{\mathcal{A}}=\underline{\underline{A}}\cdot\underline{v}_{\mathcal{L}_{xy}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
, where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{\underline{A}}=\begin{pmatrix}\cos\beta & -\sin\beta\\
\sin\beta & \cos\beta
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det{\underline{\underline{A}}}=\cos^{2}\beta+\sin^{2}\beta=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{v}_{\mathcal{L}_{xy}}=\underline{\underline{A}}^{-1}\cdot\underline{v}_{\mathcal{A}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{\underline{A}}^{-1}=\frac{1}{\det{\underline{\underline{A}}}}\cdot\left(\underline{\underline{A}}^{*}\right)^{T}=A^{T}=\begin{pmatrix}\cos\beta & \sin\beta\\
-\sin\beta & \cos\beta
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Surface coordinates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formed by the basis set: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{S}=\{\boldsymbol{s}_{1},\boldsymbol{s}_{2}\},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with one restriction: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{s}_{1}\parallel\boldsymbol{a}_{1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{\mathcal{S}}=\mathscr{L}_{\mathbb{Z}}(\mathcal{S})\subset E_{\mathcal{L}_{xy}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}_{2}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the unit cell vectors of the surface.
 By definition 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{a}_{1}$
\end_inset

 (see Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Auxiliary-coordinates"

\end_inset

 ) are parallel vectors.
 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\mathcal{S}}$
\end_inset

 is the Bravais lattice associated with the surface symmetry.
 It is easy to deduce a 
\series bold
general form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}_{2}$
\end_inset

 respect to the auxiliary basis set
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{v}_{\mathcal{A}}=\underline{\underline{S_{aux}}}\cdot\underline{v}_{S}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{s_{1}}_{\mathcal{A}}=a\cdot\begin{pmatrix}1\\
0
\end{pmatrix}\,\,;\,\,\underline{s_{2}}_{\mathcal{A}}=b\begin{pmatrix}\cos\gamma\\
\sin\gamma
\end{pmatrix}\,\,;\,\,\underline{\underline{S_{aux}}}=\begin{pmatrix}a & b\cos\gamma\\
0 & b\sin\gamma
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det{\underline{\underline{S_{aux}}}}=ab\sin\gamma
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{v}_{\mathcal{S}}=\underline{\underline{S_{aux}}}^{-1}\cdot\underline{v}_{\mathcal{A}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{\underline{S_{aux}}}^{-1}=\frac{1}{ab\sin\gamma}\cdot\begin{pmatrix}b\sin\gamma & -b\cos\gamma\\
0 & a
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Metric matrix for this space:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underline{\underline{M}}_{\mathcal{S}}=\underline{\underline{S_{aux}}}^{T}\cdot\underline{\underline{S_{aux}}}=\begin{pmatrix}a & 0\\
b\cos(\gamma) & b\sin(\gamma)
\end{pmatrix}\cdot\begin{pmatrix}a & b\cos(\gamma)\\
0 & b\sin(\gamma)
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}a^{2} & ab\cos(\gamma)\\
ab\cos(\gamma) & b^{2}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Reciprocal-space lattice
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formed by the basis set:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{G}=\left\{ \boldsymbol{k}_{1},\boldsymbol{k_{2}}\mid\boldsymbol{k}_{i}\boldsymbol{s}_{j}=2\pi\delta_{ij}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's solve the restriction in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 using the auxiliary representation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{k}_{i}\boldsymbol{s}_{j}=2\pi\delta_{ij}\,\Rightarrow\,\left(\underline{\underline{K_{aux}}}\cdot\underline{k_{i}}_{\mathcal{G}}\right)^{T}\underline{\underline{S_{aux}}}\cdot\underline{s_{j}}_{\mathcal{S}}=2\pi\delta_{ij}\,\Rightarrow\,\underline{k_{i}}_{\mathcal{G}}^{T}\cdot\left(\underline{\underline{K_{aux}}}^{T}\cdot\underline{\underline{S_{aux}}}\right)\cdot\underline{s_{j}}_{\mathcal{S}}=2\pi\delta_{ij}\label{eq:reciprocal space}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $\underline{k_{i}}_{\mathcal{G}}^{T}$
\end_inset

 and 
