\begin_layout Section
Diffraction condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have an incident particle with a given initial momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 After colliding with a surface, our particle has momentum 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}_{f}$
\end_inset

 and energy 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{p_{i}}=\boldsymbol{p}_{i\parallel}+\boldsymbol{p}_{i\perp}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{i}=T_{i\parallel}+T_{i\perp}+\epsilon_{i}\,\,\,\,,\,\,\,\, T_{\alpha}=\frac{\boldsymbol{p}_{\alpha}^{2}}{2M}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the internal energy of the particle.
 The same equations stand for the final state 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bragg law for a 2D lattice says that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{k}_{f\parallel}=\boldsymbol{k}_{i\parallel}+\boldsymbol{G}_{nm}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{p}_{i\parallel}=\hbar\boldsymbol{k}_{i\parallel}\,\,\,\,,\,\,\,\,\boldsymbol{p}_{f\parallel}=\hbar\boldsymbol{k}_{f\parallel}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{G}_{nm}$
\end_inset

 is a vector that belongs to the reciprocal space related to the surface
 lattice (in our notation,
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{G}_{nm}\in\mathcal{G}$
\end_inset

 ) and 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}_{f}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{k}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the final and initial parallel (to the surface) momentum (in 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar$
\end_inset

 units) projected on the same reciprocal space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The energy conservation law states that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $E_{i}=E_{f}\,\,\implies T_{i\parallel}+T_{i\perp}+\epsilon_{i}=T_{f\parallel}+T_{f\perp}+\epsilon_{f}\,\,\,\implies\frac{\boldsymbol{p}_{i\parallel}^{2}}{2M}+\frac{\boldsymbol{p}_{i\perp}^{2}}{2M}+\epsilon_{i}=\frac{\boldsymbol{p}_{f\parallel}^{2}}{2M}+\frac{\boldsymbol{p}_{f\perp}^{2}}{2M}+\epsilon_{f}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}_{i}^{2}-\boldsymbol{p}_{f\parallel}^{2}-\boldsymbol{p}_{f\perp}^{2}=2M\Delta\epsilon$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\epsilon=\epsilon_{f}-\epsilon_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}_{i}^{2}-\hbar^{2}\boldsymbol{k}_{f\parallel}^{2}-\boldsymbol{p}_{f\perp}^{2}=2M\Delta\epsilon$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
adding the Bragg law:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}_{i}^{2}-\hbar^{2}\left(\boldsymbol{k}_{i\parallel}+\boldsymbol{G}_{nm}\right)^{2}-\boldsymbol{p}_{f\perp}^{2}=2M\Delta\epsilon\,\,\implies\,\,\boldsymbol{p}_{i}^{2}-\hbar^{2}\left(\boldsymbol{k}_{i\parallel}^{2}+\boldsymbol{G}_{nm}^{2}+2\boldsymbol{k}_{i\parallel}\cdot\boldsymbol{G}_{nm}\right)-\boldsymbol{p}_{f\perp}^{2}=2M\Delta\epsilon$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}_{i\perp}^{2}-\hbar^{2}\left(\boldsymbol{G}_{nm}^{2}+2\boldsymbol{k}_{i\parallel}\cdot\boldsymbol{G}_{nm}\right)-\boldsymbol{p}_{f\perp}^{2}=2M\Delta\epsilon\,\,\implies\,\,\boldsymbol{p}_{f\perp}^{2}=\boldsymbol{p}_{i\perp}^{2}-\hbar^{2}\left(\boldsymbol{G}_{nm}^{2}+2\boldsymbol{k}_{i\parallel}\cdot\boldsymbol{G}_{nm}\right)-2M\Delta\epsilon$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we are describing diffraction on a surface, it holds that 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}_{f\perp}^{2}>0$
\end_inset

, which can be used to work a simple diffraction condition from the previous
 equation: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}_{i\perp}^{2}-\hbar^{2}\left(\boldsymbol{G}_{nm}^{2}+2\boldsymbol{k}_{i\parallel}\cdot\boldsymbol{G}_{nm}\right)-2M\Delta\epsilon>0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}_{i\perp}^{2}-2M\Delta\epsilon>\hbar^{2}\left(\boldsymbol{G}_{nm}^{2}+2\boldsymbol{k}_{i\parallel}\cdot\boldsymbol{G}_{nm}\right)$
